{{Infobox Muslim scholar |
occupation = [[Scholar]]| era = [[Islamic golden age]]| image = | caption = | name = '''al-Hakim Nishapuri'''| title= '''al-Hakim'''| birth_date = 3 March&nbsp;933&nbsp;CE (3 Rabi'-ul-Awwal&nbsp;321 AH)| death_date = 1 September&nbsp;1014&nbsp;CE (3 Safar&nbsp;405&nbsp;AH)| Maddhab = [[Shafi'i]]| creed = [[Ash'ari]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Mashita|first=Hiroyuki|title=Theology, Ethics and Metaphysics: Royal Asiatic Society Classics of Islam|pages=4|publisher=Routledge|date=20 Feb 2003|ISBN=070071670X}}</ref> | ethnicity = [[Persian people|Persian]]| region = | main_interests = [[Hadith]]| notable_ideas= | influences = | influenced = [[Ahmad Bayhaqi|Imam al-Bayhaqi]]<ref>Constructive Critics, Ḥadīth Literature, and the Articulation of Sunnī Islam, By Scott C. Lucas,pg. 98</ref>| works = [[Mustadrak al-Hakim]]| }}
'''Abu Abd-Allah Muhammad ibn Abd-Allah al-Hakim al-Nishapuri''' ({{lang-ar|أبو عبدالله محمد بن عبدالله الحاكم النيسابوري}}) (933 - 1014), also known as ''Ibn al-Bayyiʿ'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.islamtoday.net/english/show_detail_section.cfm?q_id=839&main_cat_id=11 |website=Islamtoday.Com |title=Al-Hakim’s ''Mustadrak'' & al-Dhahabî’s ''Talkhis'' |dead-url=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013102838/http://www.islamtoday.net/english/show_detail_section.cfm?q_id=839&main_cat_id=11 |archive-date=13 October 2008 }}</ref>) was a [[Persian people|Persian]] Sunni scholar and the leading traditionist of his age, frequently referred to as the "Imam of the [[Muhaddith]]in" or the "[[Muhaddith]] of [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]]."<ref>{{cite book|last1=Frye|first1=ed. by R.N.|title=The Cambridge history of Iran.|date=1975|publisher=Cambridge U.P. |location=London |isbn=978-0-521-20093-6 |page=471|edition=Repr.}}</ref>
==Biography== {{more refs|section|date=July 2018}} Al-Hakim, from [[Nishapur]], had vast numbers of teachers<ref>[http://members.cox.net/ameer1/bioschol.html Brief Biographies of the Eminent Scholars of Hadeeth<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060427045511/http://members.cox.net/ameer1/bioschol.html |date=2006-04-27 }}</ref> in [[Greater Khorasan|Khurasan]], Iraq, Transoxiana and elsewhere. His students included [[Ahmad Bayhaqi|Imam al-Bayhaqi]].<ref>Constructive Critics, Ḥadīth Literature, and the Articulation of Sunnī Islam, by Scott C. Lucas, pg.98</ref>
Al-Hakim wrote [[Al-Mustadrak alaa al-Sahihain]]. He started writing it in the year when he was 72 years old. He reputedly said: "I drank water from [[Zamzam Well|Zamzam]] and asked Allâh for excellence in writing books".
==Death== On the 3rd of Safar 405 al-Hakim went into the bath, came out after bathing, said, "Ah," and died wearing but a waist-cloth before he had time to put on a shirt. Later, one of al-Hakim's students, Al-Hasan ibn Ash`ath al-Qurashî said: "I saw al-Hâkim in my dream riding a horse in a handsome appearance and saying: 'Salvation.' I asked him: `Al-Hakim! In what?' He replied: 'Writing [[hadith]].'" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livingislam.org/n/6sch_e.html |title=Six Muslim Scholars |last=Haddad |first=G. F. |year=2003 |access-date=20 July 2018}}</ref>
==Legacy== [[Shah Waliullah Dehlawi|Shah Waliullah]] stated that:<ref>[[Izalat al-Khafa]] p. 77 part 7</ref> {{quote|text=A ''[[mujaddid]]'' appears at the end of every century: The ''mujaddid'' of the 1st century was [[Imam#Sunni "Imams"|Imam of Ahlul Sunnah]], [[Umar II|Umar bin Abdul Aziz]]. The ''mujaddid'' of the 2nd century was Imam of Ahlul Sunnah [[Muhammad ibn Idris ash-Shafi`i|Muhammad Idrees Shafi'i]]. The ''mujaddid'' of the 3rd century was Imam of Ahlul Sunnah [[Abu al-Hasan al-Ash'ari|Abu Hasan Ash'ari]]. The ''mujaddid'' of the 4th century was Abu Abdullah Hakim Nishapuri.}}
The Shafi'i hadith specialist [[Ibn al-Salah]] honours al-Hakim as one of the 'seven compilers of useful compilations' who has the distinction of being one of the few men to have compiled significant works in all three genres of hadith literature.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lucas|first=Scott C.|title=Constructive Critics, Ḥadīth Literature, and the Articulation of Sunnī Islam|pages=98|publisher=Brill}}</ref>
The Shafi'i historian [[al-Dhahabi]] calls him "the great hafiz and imam of the traditionists".<ref name="EI2">{{cite book |last1=Lewis |first1=B. |last2=Menage |first2=V.L. |last3=Pellat |first3=Ch. |last4=Schacht |first4=J. |title=Encyclopaedia of Islam (New Edition) |volume=Volume III (H-Iram) |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden, Netherlands |date=1986 |origyear=1st. pub. 1971 |isbn=9004081186 |page=82}}</ref>
Despite this, he had been accused{{By whom|date=June 2015}} of being a [[Shi'a]], but [[al-Subki]] stoutly denies this.<ref name="EI2"/> He rejects the label of Shi`i as baseless because [[Ibn Asakir]] includes al-Hakim among the [[Ashari]]s, who consider the Shias as [[bidah|innovators]]. Others noted to al-Hakim's sincerity in narrating hadith as the first hadith al-Hâkim narrated is: :May Allah make radiant the face of one who heard one of my sayings and then carried it to others. It may be that one carries understanding without being a person of understanding; it may be that one carries understanding to someone who possesses more understanding than he.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}
==Works== He authored the following works among others: * ''Al-Abwâb'' ("The Chapters") * ''Al-Amâlî'' ("The Dictations") * ''Amâlî al-`Ashiyyât'' ("Night Dictations") * ''Fadâ'il al-Shâfi`î'' ("The Immense Merits of al-Shâfi`î") * ''Fawâ'id al-Nusakh'' ("Benefits of the Copies") * ''Fawâ'id al-Khurâsâniyyîn'' ("Benefits of the People of Khurâsân") * ''Al-Iklîl fî Dalâ'il al-Nubuwwa'' ("The Diadem: The Marks of Prophethood") * ''Al-`Ilal'' ("The Defects of Hadîth") * ''Mâ Tafarrada bi Ikhrâjihi Kullu Wâhidin min al-Imâmayn'' ("Reports Found Only in al-Bukhârî or Only in Muslim") * ''Al-Madkhal ilâ `Ilm al-Sahîh'' ("Introduction to the Science of Sound Reports") * ''Ma`rifat Anwâ` `Ulûm al-Hadîth'' ("Knowledge of the Different Types of the Hadîth Sciences") * ''Al-Mustadrak `alâ al-Sahîhayn'' ("Supplement for What is Missing From al-Bukhârî and Muslim") * ''Muzakkâ al-Akhbâr'' ("Verified Reports") * ''Al-Sahîhân'' ("The Two Books of sahîh Hadîths") * ''Al-Talkhîs'' ("The Summary") * ''Tarâjim al-Musnad `alâ Shart al-Sahîhayn'' ("The Reports of Ahmad's Musnad That Match the Criteria of the Two Books of Sahîh") * ''Tarâjim al-Shuyûkh'' ("Biographies of the Shaykhs") * ''Târîkh `Ulamâ' Ahl Naysabûr'' ("History of the Scholars of Naysabûr")
